📊 Confusion Matrix & Evaluation Metrics in Machine Learning
🔍 What is a Confusion Matrix?

A Confusion Matrix is a table used to evaluate the performance of a classification model.

It compares:

✅ Actual values
with
✅ Predicted values
📦 Structure of Confusion Matrix

For Binary Classification:

Actual / Predicted	Positive	Negative
Positive	True Positive (TP)	False Negative (FN)
Negative	False Positive (FP)	True Negative (TN)
🧠 Understanding the Terms
✅ True Positive (TP)

Model correctly predicts Positive.

Example:

Email is spam
Model says spam ✔️
✅ True Negative (TN)

Model correctly predicts Negative.

Example:

Email is not spam
Model says not spam ✔️
❌ False Positive (FP)

Model predicts positive incorrectly.

Example:

Email is not spam
Model says spam ❌

Also called:

Type I Error
❌ False Negative (FN)

Model predicts negative incorrectly.

Example:

Email is spam
Model says not spam ❌

Also called:

Type II Error
🎯 Example Confusion Matrix
Actual / Predicted	Spam	Not Spam
Spam	50	10
Not Spam	5	35

Here:

TP = 50
FN = 10
FP = 5
TN = 35
📈 Evaluation Metrics

These metrics are calculated using TP, TN, FP, FN.

1️⃣ Accuracy

Accuracy means:

👉 How many predictions are correct?

Formula:

